THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS EFFORT IS TO ESTABLISH A PILOT INSTITUTE FOR ADDITIVE MANUFACTURING TO ACCELERATE RESEARCH, DEVELOPMENT, AND DEMONSTRATION IN ADDITIVE MANUFACTURING AND TRANSITION TECHNOLOGY TO MANUFACTURING ENTERPRISES WITHIN THE UNITED STATES. 2.0 SCOPE: THE GOAL OF THE PILOT INSTITUTE IS TO CREATE A SUSTAINABLE MODEL TO INCREASE THE SUCCESSFUL TRANSITION OF ADDITIVE MANUFACTURING TECHNOLOGY THROUGH ADVANCED MANUFACTURING INNOVATION, CREATE AN ADAPTIVE WORKFORCE CAPABLE OF MEETING INDUSTRY NEEDS, FURTHER INCREASING DOMESTIC COMPETITIVENESS, AND MEET DOD, DOE, NASA, AND OTHER PARTICIPATING AGENCY REQUIREMENTS. 3.0 BACKGROUND: THE NATIONAL NETWORK FOR MANUFACTURING INNOVATION (NNMI) CONSISTS OF UP TO 15 INSTITUTES FOR MANUFACTURING INNOVATION AROUND THE COUNTRY. THE INSTITUTES WILL BRING TOGETHER INDUSTRY, UNIVERSITIES AND COMMUNITY COLLEGES, FEDERAL AGENCIES, AND REGIONAL AND STATE ORGANIZATIONS TO ACCELERATE INNOVATION BY INVESTING IN INDUSTRIALLY-RELEVANT MANUFACTURING TECHNOLOGIES WITH BROAD APPLICATIONS. THE ADDITIVE MANUFACTURING INNOVATION INSTITUTE (AMII) IS THE PILOT INSTITUTE AND WILL SERVE AS THE MODEL FOR FUTURE NNMI INSTITUTES.
